1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,435
It is easy as to understand the spread of our data visually.

2

00:00:04,435  -->  00:00:09,780
The most common visual for quantitative data is known as a histogram.

3

00:00:09,780  -->  00:00:15,165
In this video, we will take a look at exactly how histograms are constructed.

4

00:00:15,165  -->  00:00:18,772
In order to understand how histograms are constructed,

5

00:00:18,772  -->  00:00:21,640
consider we have the following data-set.

6

00:00:21,640  -->  00:00:24,400
First, we need to bin our data.

7

00:00:24,400  -->  00:00:29,609
You as the histogram creator ultimately choose how the binning occurs.

8

00:00:29,609  -->  00:00:33,625
Here, I have chosen our bins as one to four,

9

00:00:33,625  -->  00:00:37,930
five to eight, 9-12 and 13-16.

10

00:00:37,930  -->  00:00:41,699
Because these first four values are between one and four,

11

00:00:41,699  -->  00:00:43,495
they go into the first bin.

12

00:00:43,495  -->  00:00:46,870
These next three values are between five and eight,

13

00:00:46,870  -->  00:00:48,400
so they fall in the next bin,

14

00:00:48,400  -->  00:00:54,040
then these two values fall in this bin and 15 falls into our last bin.

15

00:00:54,040  -->  00:01:00,070
The number of values in each bin determine the height of each histogram bar.

16

00:01:00,070  -->  00:01:04,860
Changing the bins will result in a slightly different visual.

17

00:01:04,860  -->  00:01:08,340
There really isn't a right answer to choosing our bins,

18

00:01:08,340  -->  00:01:12,875
and in most cases software will choose the appropriate bins for us.

19

00:01:12,875  -->  00:01:15,970
But it is something to be aware of.
